/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSugar as a global commodity has shaped our world, impacting cultures and influencing cuisine. The heritage of sugar is investigated in the context of globalization and tourism development. Facets of the sugar story include colonization, enslavement, decolonization and postcolonial tourism while cultural practices traced to sugar include carnival and confectionery as souvenirs. However, what happens where sugar is still produced, where production is in decline, or where the country has exited from producing? How is sugar engrained in national identities and how does this influence tourism? From the perspectives of contributing authors, destination examples include Brazil, India, Taiwan, New Zealand, Australia, Barbados, Cuba, Dominican Republic, St. Lucia, and St. Kitts. This is the first work examining sugar heritage in relation to tourism from a global perspective, identifying related tourism directions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCulture and tourism. 0aHeritage tourism. 0aSugar industryxHistory. 0aSugar tradexEconomic aspects. 0aSugar tradexHistory. 0aSugar tradexSocial aspects. 0aSugarxSocial aspects. 0aTourism. 4aCultural studies. 4aGeneral & world history. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  acolonisation.  aglobalisation.  aheritage.  aslavery.  asouvenirs.  asugar.  atourism development.1 aBest, Mechelle N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleave, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodds, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlecha, Angela Cabral, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForristal